==English==

===Etymology===
French ''[[purger]]'', Latin ''[[purgare]]'', from ''[[purus]]'', "clean", "pure".

===Noun===
{{en-noun-reg}}

# the act of purging
# something that purges; a [[purgative]]
# forcible removal of undesirable people from political activity, etc.

===Verb===
{{en-infl-reg-other-e|purg|e}}

#''(transitive)''  to [[clean]] [[thorough]]ly; to [[cleanse]]; to [[rid]] of [[impurity|impurities]]
#''(transitive)'' (''religion'') to [[free]] from [[sin]], [[guilt]], or the [[burden]] or [[responsibility]] of [[misdeed]]s
#''(transitive)'' (''medicine'') to void the [[bowel]]
#''(transitive)'' (''law'') to [[clear]] of a [[charge]], [[suspicion]], or [[imputation]]

